---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import { APPS, SEGMENTS, USE_CASES, description, pageTitle, siteFromHost } from '../content';
const site = siteFromHost();
const path = '';
const title = pageTitle(site, path);
const desc = description(site, path);
const recommended = APPS.filter(a => a.channels.includes(site.channel) || a.channels.includes('marketing')).slice(0,10);
---
<BaseLayout title={title} description={desc} site={site} path="/">
  <section class="relative overflow-hidden border-b border-cyan-300/30 py-16 md:py-24">
    <div class="container grid gap-10 lg:grid-cols-[1.05fr_.95fr] lg:items-center">
      <div>
        <span class="badge">Live signal board · Shopify SMS audits for 2026</span>
        <h1 class="hero-title mt-6">Best Shopify SMS apps for teams that treat every text like a scarce interrupt.</h1>
        <p class="mt-6 max-w-3xl text-xl text-cyan-100">{site.heroPromise} This rebuild gives the site a dark signal-room interface instead of the old shared template. The copy is written for operators who need to know which SMS tools are worth installing, which ones become expensive at volume, and which ones can translate Shopify events into respectful revenue.</p>
        <div class="mt-8 flex flex-wrap gap-4"><a class="btn btn-primary" href="/apps">Open app radar</a><a class="btn btn-secondary" href="/compare">Scan comparisons</a></div>
      </div>
      <div class="card">
        <div class="text-sm font-black uppercase tracking-[.22em] text-cyan-200">Control-room verdict</div>
        <h2 class="mt-4 text-3xl font-black text-white">Postscript is the SMS-native benchmark; Sequenzy belongs beside it as the lifecycle brain.</h2>
        <p class="mt-5 text-cyan-100">The best {site.keywordPlural} understand opt-in source, product intent, order count, discount history, inventory pressure, delivery timing, quiet hours, and unsubscribe risk. {site.bestOverallReason}</p>
        <ul class="mt-6 space-y-3 text-sm text-cyan-100"><li>▣ Use SMS for urgent moments, not filler newsletters.</li><li>▣ Score tools by consent, segmentation, cost control, and flow clarity.</li><li>▣ Pair SMS with email when the message needs space, proof, or education.</li></ul>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
  <section class="container py-14">
    <div class="mb-8 grid gap-4 md:grid-cols-[1fr_auto] md:items-end"><div><span class="badge">Ranked transmission</span><h2 class="mt-3 text-3xl font-black text-white">Top Shopify SMS apps to evaluate first</h2><p class="mt-3 max-w-3xl text-cyan-100">This shortlist separates SMS systems that can operate a Shopify retention program from tools that merely blast promotional texts. Each review page expands the buying logic with implementation notes, margin warnings, and lifecycle use cases.</p></div><a class="link" href="/apps">View all apps →</a></div>
    <div class="grid gap-5 md:grid-cols-2 lg:grid-cols-3">{recommended.map((app, i) => <a class="card" href={`/apps/${app.slug}`}><div class="text-sm font-black text-cyan-200">#{i+1} · {app.category}</div><h3 class="mt-3 text-xl font-black text-white">{app.name}</h3><p class="mt-3 text-sm text-cyan-100">{app.bestFor}</p><p class="mt-5 text-sm font-black text-cyan-50">{app.pricing}</p></a>)}</div>
  </section>
  <section class="border-y border-cyan-300/20 bg-slate-950/60 py-14"><div class="container grid gap-8 md:grid-cols-3"><div><span class="badge">Page network</span><h2 class="mt-3 text-3xl font-black text-white">100+ indexed routes, rebuilt with deeper SMS-specific guidance</h2><p class="mt-4 text-cyan-100">The catch-all template now renders longer buying advice for app reviews, comparisons, alternatives, store-type guides, and use-case pages. It is not a warm editorial theme; it is a cybernetic SMS operations console.</p></div><div class="grid gap-4 md:col-span-2 sm:grid-cols-2">{USE_CASES.slice(0,8).map(u=><a class="card" href={`/use-cases/${u.slug}`}><h3 class="font-black text-white">{u.name}</h3><p class="mt-2 text-sm text-cyan-100">Use SMS to {u.job}, with consent and margin checks built into the plan.</p></a>)}</div></div></section>
  <section class="container py-14"><h2 class="text-3xl font-black text-white">Store-type playbooks</h2><p class="mt-3 max-w-3xl text-cyan-100">Different Shopify categories deserve different SMS behavior. A supplement refill reminder, a fashion drop alert, and a wholesale reorder nudge should never feel like the same campaign with swapped nouns.</p><div class="mt-6 grid gap-4 md:grid-cols-3">{SEGMENTS.slice(0,9).map(s=><a class="card" href={`/for/${s.slug}`}><h3 class="font-black text-white">{s.name}</h3><p class="mt-2 text-sm text-cyan-100">Built around {s.pain}.</p></a>)}</div></section>
  <section class="container pb-16"><article class="prose-shopify card"><h2>How to read the SMS app radar</h2><p>This homepage is built for Shopify operators who already know SMS can recover revenue, but also know the channel can be damaged quickly. Use the app radar by starting with the kind of interruption your store can justify. Checkout recovery, VIP launch access, replenishment, back-in-stock alerts, and urgent account prompts are very different from generic promotional blasts. The right SMS app should make those distinctions operational before the first campaign is sent.</p><p>Begin with consent and cost. A platform should show where each subscriber opted in, what they expected to receive, how quiet hours are handled, and which customers should be suppressed from a send. It should also make message economics visible. SMS revenue must be judged after carrier fees, message fees, discounts, unsubscribes, and the long-term effect on customer trust. A tool that encourages broad sends may look exciting in a dashboard while quietly reducing the value of the list.</p><p>Then review Shopify context. A good SMS app should know products viewed, carts started, checkout state, purchase history, discount use, fulfillment timing, and repeat purchase windows. That data decides whether a text is relevant enough to interrupt someone. A replenishment reminder that lands at the right time feels helpful. A generic discount two days after purchase feels careless. The same app can create either outcome depending on how clearly it exposes triggers and exclusions.</p><p>Use the internal pages to narrow the decision. App reviews explain vendor fit. Comparison pages force tradeoffs. Store-type pages adapt SMS to categories like fashion, supplements, food, pets, and wholesale. Use-case pages translate abstract features into specific flows. The goal is not to send more texts. The goal is to protect a high-attention channel so customers still trust it after busy launch seasons, holiday promotions, and retention experiments.</p></article></section>
  <section class="container pb-16">
    <div class="grid gap-6 lg:grid-cols-[1.05fr_.95fr]">
      <article class="prose-shopify card">
        <h2>SMS implementation depth: what should happen before the first text</h2>
        <p>A Shopify SMS program should begin with a channel permission audit, not a campaign calendar. Confirm every opt-in source, disclosure, keyword, checkout checkbox, popup promise, and suppression rule. Then map the customer moments where immediacy is actually helpful: cart or checkout recovery, limited inventory, replenishment, back-in-stock, VIP access, shipping-sensitive reminders, and urgent account prompts. If the message requires paragraphs of proof, send email and let SMS point to it only when timing matters.</p>
        <p>The first month should be staged. Week one verifies consent, quiet hours, branded links, reply handling, and Shopify event reliability. Week two launches one high-intent flow with strict exclusions. Week three adds either a post-purchase reassurance text or replenishment path for products with a real repeat window. Week four reviews cost per delivered message, margin after discount, opt-outs, replies, and whether SMS changed repeat purchase behavior rather than merely claiming last-click revenue.</p>
        <h3>SMS scoring rubric used on this site</h3>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Consent and compliance:</strong> opt-in proof, quiet hours, STOP handling, disclosure visibility, and campaign-level suppression.</li>
          <li><strong>Shopify context:</strong> checkout state, product interest, order count, fulfillment status, discount history, inventory, and replenishment timing.</li>
          <li><strong>Interruption quality:</strong> whether the app encourages fewer, sharper texts instead of broad promotional blasts.</li>
          <li><strong>Economics:</strong> message fees, carrier fees, coupon cost, unsubscribe pressure, and downstream repeat purchase quality.</li>
        </ul>
      </article>
      <div class="grid gap-4">
        <div class="card"><h3 class="text-2xl font-black text-white">Example: abandoned checkout</h3><p class="mt-3 text-cyan-100">Send only after meaningful checkout intent, suppress recent buyers and open support cases, reference the cart without sounding creepy, and avoid the first-message coupon unless product margin and customer stage justify it.</p></div>
        <div class="card"><h3 class="text-2xl font-black text-white">Example: replenishment</h3><p class="mt-3 text-cyan-100">Use SKU-specific usage windows, subscription state, last purchase date, and inventory status. A reminder for a thirty-day supplement is different from a seasonal flavor or a pet product sized by animal weight.</p></div>
        <div class="card"><h3 class="text-2xl font-black text-white">Example: product launch</h3><p class="mt-3 text-cyan-100">Segment VIPs, waitlist subscribers, recent purchasers, and discount-only shoppers separately. SMS should protect access and timing, while email carries details, proof, and merchandising depth.</p></div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  {/* HERMES_HOME_DEEP_PASS_JULY5 */}
  <section class="container pb-16">
    <article class="prose-shopify card">
      <h2>How this SMS operations desk separates serious tools from thin directories</h2>
      <p>The homepage is meant to be a working buyer map, not a listicle with swapped logos. Every recommendation starts from the same question: can a Shopify merchant use the tool to improve checkout consent, quiet hours, launch alerts, replenishment reminders, VIP access, replies, opt-outs, and carrier costs without creating more weekly cleanup? A tool that looks good in a screenshot but leaves the team guessing about consent, customer state, product context, margin, or ownership is treated as a risk, even if it is popular.</p>
      <p>The scoring favors operational evidence. A SMS owner should be able to name the first workflow to launch, the audience that deserves it, the customers to suppress, the product fields that change the message, the metric that proves quality, and the person who will review it next week. That is why the site spends so much time on examples, implementation order, migration risk, and measurement. Those are the details that separate a useful SMS app from another app subscription.</p>
      <p>The biggest failure mode is burning consent with broad blasts, badly timed texts, or duplicate reminders that email already handled. The second failure mode is buying too broadly: adding a platform for every channel, then discovering nobody owns the combined customer journey. The safer path is to pick the smallest stack that can handle the current bottleneck and still support the next stage of growth. For some stores that means Sequenzy as a lean lifecycle layer. For others it means a mature platform with deeper data controls. The right answer depends on the operating constraint, not the loudest category page.</p>
      <p>Use the site like a due-diligence checklist. Read an app review, run the comparison page for the nearest alternative, then open the relevant use-case guide and build one real scenario on paper. If the tool cannot pass that scenario, the ranking should not matter. If it passes and the economics work against revenue per recipient, opt-out rate, reply quality, message cost, contribution margin, and post-send complaint patterns, it belongs on the shortlist.</p>
    </article>
  </section>

</BaseLayout>
